In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

# 1.1 query: 
df = pd.read_sql("SELECT mobile_food_locations.Address, mobile_food_permits.Applicant, count(*) \
                    FROM mobile_food_locations \
                    INNER JOIN mobile_food_permits \
                    ON mobile_food_permits.permit = mobile_food_schedule.permit \
                    INNER JOIN mobile_food_schedule \
                    ON mobile_food_locations.locationid = mobile_food_schedule.locationid \
                    WHERE status=='APPROVED' \
                    GROUP BY Address \
                    ORDER BY count(*)", db)
df['Applicant'].value_counts().head(5) # Count the values

By far, the most common crime in SF is grand theft from a locked automobile. In Southern District, the trend is disturbingly the same, and the crime rates for the other top categories are roughly homogeneous with respect to the entire city. This suggests that Southern District is a fair representation of the crime committed in San Francisco, and if a random sample of crimes were taken from Southern District to represent the entire city, the results would not be too far off. Of course, with the data provided, we would rather simply randomly sample from the entire city, but if it was needed the other choice (with less data, and therefore effort and/or money) would be reasonable.

In [16]:
crime_grandtheft = pd.read_sql("SELECT DayOfWeek, Lon, Lat \
                        FROM crime \
                        WHERE Descript = 'GRAND THEFT FROM LOCKED AUTO' \
                        AND DayOfWeek IN ('Friday', 'Saturday')", db)
gt_map = Basemap(projection="merc", llcrnrlon=-122.55, llcrnrlat=37.69, urcrnrlon=-122.35, urcrnrlat=37.81, resolution="h", area_thresh = 0.1)

gt_map.drawcoastlines()
gt_map.drawmapboundary()
gt_map.drawcounties()
gt_map.readshapefile("SF Find Neighborhoods/geo_export_dd4c4138-2501-498e-86f4-06d7827b2d53", "geo_export_dd4c4138-2501-498e-86f4-06d7827b2d53")
gt_map.fillcontinents(color="grey")

for lon, lat, day in zip(crime_grandtheft.Lon, crime_grandtheft.Lat, crime_grandtheft.DayOfWeek):
    x, y = gt_map(lon, lat)
    color = "b"
    if (day == "Saturday"):
        color = "r"
    gt_map.plot(x, y, color + "o", markersize = 4, alpha = 0.5)
    
plt.title("Map of Grand Theft on Autos for Friday and Saturday")
plt.show()

KEY: Blue - Friday | Red - Saturday

Assuming that all districts have complete data, we can see that perhaps in specific smaller regions of the city, there are very small differences as to where grand thefts occur on Fridays versus Saturdays, but in general, both days have both a similar amount of grand thefts and roughly the same distribution. Grand thefts, on Fridays and Saturdays at least, are very concentrated in the northeastern quadrant of the city, where everywhere else has a mild to moderate seemingly uniform sprinkling. There are some specifically small regions like Golden Gate Park and central residential areas that have a significantly reduced rate of grand thefts in general.

KEY: Red - Parking Garages | Blue - Parking Lots

It is apparent that parking garages, which can hold far more vehicles since they are vertical as well, are far more common in northeastern SF where the financial district and touristy regions typically hold more people in such a congested space. The Embarcadero area specifically has a great deal of parking garages nearby. Parking lots, though, are far more common in areas where space is more spread out relative to the dense city areas, such as east-central city and along Golden Gate Park. The use of parking lots elsewhere is awfully common along major roads where parking is needed for markets, workplaces, and other facilities. So, in conclusion, water appears to have nothing to do with the density of parking lots; it is the location and relative utility of them that determines their density in a particular region.

Now I would like to know the distribution of the capacities of parking garages and parking lots in SF.

In [22]:
garages_g = parking[parking["GarOrLot"]=="G"]

Parking lot capacity is far more skewed right with far more parking lots under 100 capacity than parking garages, as logically expected. Lots outnumber garages almost three-fold; the average garage capacity is around 215 (median 116), whereas lots have about 85 spots on average (median 30.5). The abundance of small businesses throughout the city (and relatively small private lots) lower the mean of the parking lots making the difference between garages more stark.

An odd finding is the lot of size 9000; this was determined to be Candlestick Park via SQL. Such influential values affects the mean and variance quite a bit; these could be removed if more analysis was performed.

Question 5: Is median selling price correlated with residence turnover? And in which zip codes is this most prevalent?

In [27]:
med_turnover = pd.read_sql("SELECT RegionName, MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes, Turnover_AllHomes \
                FROM zillow \
                WHERE MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes > 0 \
                GROUP BY RegionName", db)
med_per_sqft = med_turnover.loc[:,'MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes'].tolist()
turnover_rate = med_turnover.loc[:,'Turnover_AllHomes'].tolist()

The sample size is 25, so any conclusions will have to be taken lightly (but this cannot be fixed, per se, if we still would like to look at zip codes; blocks may be a different story). We also have to see if both variables are approximately normally distributed - but with a sample size of 25, this will have to be strikingly visually obvious to consider any results valuable.

In [28]:
n, bins, patches = plt.hist(med_per_sqft, 15, normed=1, facecolor='blue', alpha=0.7)
plt.xlabel('Median Home Price Per SQFT')
plt.title(r'Median Home Price Per Square Foot Per SF Zipcode')
plt.show()
In [29]:
ln_turnover_rate = [math.log(y) for y in turnover_rate] # ln transform
n, bins, patches = plt.hist(ln_turnover_rate, 10, normed=1, facecolor='blue', alpha=0.7)
plt.xlabel('ln(Turnover Rate)')
plt.title(r'Log-Transform of Turnover Rate')
plt.show()

From the histograms above, we can see rough normality (both are moderately skewed right though) in both the median selling price per square foot and the log-transformed turnover rate data. Thus, we can continue with our analysis despite the fact that we have had to transform a variable to make a conclusion about linear correlation (but the conclusion will be stated exactly as it should in a moment).

In [30]:
pearson_corr_coeff = pearsonr(med_per_sqft, ln_turnover_rate)[0]
pearson_corr_coeff
Out[30]:
0.42517997389053203

The Pearson's correlation coefficient is about 0.4252, signaling mild positive linear correlation between median selling price per square foot and natural log of turnover rate. This means that, in general, as median home price per square foot increases, turnover rate also increases. This implies that residents in zip codes with generally higher priced homes move more often in San Francisco (with the fact kept in mind that we are making this conclusion of linear correlation WITH a log-transformed variable). It should be noted that when disregarding the skewed nature of the non-transformed turnover rates, the Pearson's correlation coefficient is about 0.3874, but it is questionable whether or not this correlation can be interpretted well given the violation of assumptions. We will now look at which zip codes the median price per square foot is greatest in, and make any other conclusions we can find. (From here on out, we will return to analyzing non-transformed turnover rate.)

zips = gpd.read_file("zip/cb_2015_us_zcta510_500k.shp")
